questionTemplates.text:
W: When are you going to move into the dorm, Randy?
M: I'm not sure. I'd like to be able to wait until after summer vacation.
{a}

W: Do you think that Jim really fell in love with Alison?
M: Of course! I've never seen him spend so much time and energy on the same person.
{a}

M: It's so hot today. I simply can't work. I wish there were a fan in this room.
W: So do I. I'll fall asleep if I stay here any longer.
{a}

W: Now what seems to be the trouble, Mr Smith?
M: I am running a temperature, and I'm coughing badly.
{a}

M: Hi, Jane, do you have some change? I have to make a call on the pay phone.
W: Pay phone? Why not use my mobile phone? Here you are.
{a}

M: Where are you from?
F: Northern Canada.
{a}

W: Would you please give me change for a pound? It's for the phone box.
M: Here you are.
{a}

M: Can I see Titanic on Sunday?
W: I'm not sure.
{a}

F: Did you go to the meeting yesterday?
M: Yes, I did. A famous scientist gave a talk at the meeting.
{a}

M: Now, what seems to be the trouble, Mrs. Stephens?
W: I've been very dizzy lately, and last night I had some chest pain.
{a}

W: Do you know how I can stop drinking too much coffee?
M: No, but I wish I did. I spend too much money at cafe's.
{a}

M: The front tyre is flat, and the seat needs to be raised.
W: Why not take it to Mr. Smith?
{a}

W: Do you think we should bring a present to Mary's party?
M: No, it's not her birthday. We'll just bring a bottle of wine.
{a}

M: I'm starving. Do we still have any pie left from the dinner yesterday?
W: Oh, Julia invited her friends over in the afternoon and they ate it all.
{a}

M: Robert wants to go with us to the party.
W: But our car is too small to take four people.
{a}

M: I hear the Sunflower Health Club on Third Street is good!
W: Not right now! I used to go there. I thought it was great because it was real cheap. But the problem was it was always crowded. Sometimes, I had to wait to use the machines.
{a}

F: Let's go shopping this afternoon.
M: Sorry. I have a friend to meet.
{a}

W: He is sleeping.
M: Don't bother him. He worked all night last night.
{a}

W: Yes, is there something wrong?
M: I think you've made a mistake. This isn't what I ordered. I asked for the red jacket, not the blue one!
{a}

M: Hello, I'm a senior student. Could you tell me whether this reference room is only for faculty members?
W: No, it's a also open to the postgraduates; and undergraduates can come too if they're got professors' written permission.
{a}

M: How about joining me for a cup of coffee?
W: I'd love to, but I'm exhausted. I was up till 3 this morning, writing a paper for my literature class.
{a}

W: Have you found your dictionary?
M: Yes, I found it under my bed.
{a}

W: How did your writing go this morning? Is the book coming along alright?
M: I'm not sure. I think the rest of it will be difficult to write.
{a}

W: Have you seen that huge new building going up near the market?
M: Yes, I can't figure out what it's supposed to be. Not an apartment building? Not a hotel? Probably a department store.
{a}

W: I think your article in the school newspaper is right on target, and your viewpoints have certainly convinced me.
M: Thanks, but in view of the general responses, you and I are definitely in the minority.
{a}

W: What's that book you're reading at the moment? It seems that you're interested in it.
M: Oh, the title of the book is Life on Earth. Um, I got it because of the television program.
{a}
